{
  "text": "Importantly, it has recently been shown that a conserved domain called a chromodomain, which occurs in Polycombgroup proteins, as well as in other proteins involved in chromatin remodeling such as the HP1 and CHD families [CITATION_1] and the histone acetyltransferase MOF, is an RNAbinding module [CITATION_2] . The chromodomain controls sequence and target specificity [CITATION_3] and different Polycomb-group protein complexes function at different genomic sites [CITATION_4] . Chromodomaincontaining proteins are also involved in position effect variegation [CITATION_5] . In addition, a non-coding RNA has been shown to act as a transcriptional co-activator for steroid receptors [CITATION_6] , whose action also requires chromatin remodeling and the recruitment of histone acetyltransferases [CITATION_7] . Thus chromatin structure and hence gene expression in higher eukaryotes appears to be controlled not just by protein factors but also by trans-acting RNA signals.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "24747982",
    "[CITATION_2]": "4396701",
    "[CITATION_3]": "24747982",
